projects:
[{'title': 'EndSVCHack at the Global Summit to End Violence in Conflict', 'date': {'start': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2014}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2014}}, 'description': 'At the Global Summit to End Sexual Violence in Conflict on the 10-13 June at the Excel centre, London, the FCO, together with the Embassy of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, Chayn and MakeSense will host a hackathon. This ‘Diplohack’ will bring together coders and developers from across the world, alongside diplomats, social entrepreneurs, experts on sexual violence in conflict, survivors and NGO representatives. The aim is to produce technology-driven solutions supporting the four aims of the summit:

To improve investigations/documentation of sexual violence in conflict;
To provide greater support and assistance and reparation for survivors, including child survivors, of sexual violence;
To ensure sexual and gender based violence responses and the promotion of gender equality are fully integrated in all peace and security efforts, including security and justice sector reform; and
To improve international strategic co-ordination.

Over three days (10-12 June), participants will first generate ideas for the most useful technical solutions. They will then work in small start-up style teams to turn these ideas into prototypes and present them to a high-profile judging panel which includes; Jody Williams (Nobel Peace Prize Laureate) Fran Perrin (founder & director of the Indigo Trust) Laetitia van den Assum, (Dutch Ambassador to the UK) Chris Taggart (Co Founder and CEO of Open Corporates) Hibaaq Osman (Founder and CEO of Karama), and Niccoló A. Figá-Talamanca (Secretary General No Peace Without Justice).', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Weijer', 'last_name': 'Losecaat Vermeer', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Senior policy officer at Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Netherlands'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Hera', 'last_name': 'Hussain', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Founder & CEO, Chayn (on mat leave) I Ashoka Fellow | Forbes Under 30 | MIT Innovators Under 35'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Charlotte', 'last_name': 'Talens', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Ik begeleid (management)teams, organisaties en hun leiders (in binnen- en buitenland) bij het oplossen van complexe vraagstukken en het vinden van ruimte voor beweging waar het vastzit. (vml-diplomaat)'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Jon', 'last_name': 'P.', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Press secretary'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Faeza Asad', 'last_name': 'Khan', 'name': None, 'headline': 'WISH2ACTION Deputy Director Commercial at Internatioal Planned Parenthood Federation'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Adam', 'last_name': 'Bye', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Deputy UK High Commissioner to South Africa at British High Commission Pretoria'}]}, {'title': '#DiploHack', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}}, 'description': 'For Social Media Week 2013 in London, the Dutch and the Swedish embassies teamed up to host a #DiploHack event at Hub Westminster, in collaboration with the MakeSense community.

The aim of the event was to connect new networks and explore new forms of collaborations around relevant diplomacy topics. The event brought together actors from across sectors (NGOs, diplomats, artists, social entrepreneurs and corporates) who came together to 'hack' diplomacy by knowledge exchange and collaborative and creative problem solving.

We will be co-created innovative solutions based on the power of the internet and social media around two specific challenges:

1. "How can creative collaboration in the arts enhance freedom of speech and tolerance around the world?"

2. "How open data and technology can tackle inefficiencies in the food supply chain?"

The project is intended to look at new ways of diplomacy and collaboration in international relations. 

Wired.co.uk came along and wrote up what it saw: http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2013-09/27/diplohack

The successful day’s event featured plenary speeches and interactive workshops aiming to show how Dutch politicians and planners have succeeded in building high cycling levels with public support and consider how this can be achieved in Manchester.
Speakers at the conference included leading Dutch and UK experts and politicians in the fields of cycling and urban planning, including: Wim van der Wijk from Royal Haskoning DHV, John Whitelegg, Professor of Sustainable Transport at John Moores University Liverpool, Wim Bot from the Dutch Cyclists Union, Rod King from Twenty is Plenty and was chaired by Philip Darnton, President of CycleNation.
